# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: matter-protocol-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] BLE and Classic Bluetooth use different sets of radio frequencies, and although BLE is independent of classic Bluetooth and has no direct compatibility, Bluetooth Basic Rate/Enhanced Data Rate (BR/EDR) and BLE can coexist.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] The original specification was developed by Nokia in 2006 under the name Wibree, which was integrated into Bluetooth 4.0 in December 2009 as Bluetooth Low Energy.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Mobile operating systems including iOS, Android, Windows Phone and BlackBerry, as well as the desktop computer operating systems macOS, Linux, Windows 8, Windows 10 and Windows 11, natively support Bluetooth Low Energy.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Bluetooth Low Energy is distinct from the previous (often called "classic") Bluetooth Basic Rate/Enhanced Data Rate (BR/EDR) protocol, but the two protocols can both be supported by one device: the Bluetooth 4.0 specification permits devices to implement either or both of the LE and BR/EDR systems.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Bluetooth Low Energy uses the same 2.4 GHz radio frequencies as classic Bluetooth, which allows dual-mode devices to share a single radio antenna, but uses a simpler modulation system.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] In 2011, the Bluetooth SIG announced the Bluetooth Smart logo so as to clarify compatibility between the new low-energy devices and other Bluetooth devices.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] With the May 2016 Bluetooth SIG branding information, the Bluetooth SIG began phasing out the Bluetooth Smart and Bluetooth Smart Ready logos and word marks and reverted to using the Bluetooth logo and word mark in a new blue color.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] The Bluetooth SIG identifies a number of markets for low-energy technology, particularly in the smart home, health, sport, and fitness sectors.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] In 2001, researchers at Nokia determined various scenarios that contemporary wireless technologies did not address.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] The company began developing a wireless technology adapted from the Bluetooth standard which would provide lower power usage and cost while minimizing its differences from Bluetooth technology.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] The results were published in 2004 using the name Bluetooth Low End Extension.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] After further development with partners, in particular Logitech and within the European project MIMOSA, and actively promoted and supported by STMicroelectronics since its early stage, the technology was released to the public in October 2006 with the brand name Wibree.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] After negotiations with Bluetooth SIG members, an agreement was reached in June 2007 to include Wibree in a future Bluetooth specification as a Bluetooth ultra-low-power technology.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] The technology was marketed as Bluetooth Smart and integration into version 4.0 of the Core Specification was completed in early 2010.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] The first smartphone to implement the 4.0 specification was the iPhone 4S, released in October 2011.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] A number of other manufacturers released Bluetooth Low Energy Ready devices in 2012.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] The Bluetooth SIG officially unveiled Bluetooth 5 on 16 June 2016 during a media event in London.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] One change on the marketing side was that the point number was dropped, so it is now just called Bluetooth 5 (and not Bluetooth 5.0 or 5.0 LE like for Bluetooth 4.0).
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] This decision was made to "simplify marketing, and communicate user benefits more effectively".
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] An "advertising packet" in Bluetooth parlance is the information that is exchanged between two devices *before* pairing, i.e. when they are not connected.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] For example, advertising packets allow a device to display to the user the name of another Bluetooth device before pairing with it.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Bluetooth 5 increased the data length of this advertising packet.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] The length of this packet in Bluetooth 4.x was 31 bytes (for broadcast topology).
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] The Bluetooth SIG officially released Mesh Profile and Mesh Model specifications on 18 July 2017.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Mesh specification enables using Bluetooth Low Energy for many-to-many device communications for home automation, sensor networks, and other applications, where sensors, robots, smartphones, and other equipment need to be coordinated.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Borrowing from the original Bluetooth specification, the Bluetooth SIG defines several profiles – specifications for how a device works in a particular application – for low-energy devices.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Manufacturers are expected to implement the appropriate specifications for their device in order to ensure compatibility.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] A device may contain implementations of multiple profiles.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] The majority of current Low Energy application profiles are based on the Generic Attribute Profile (GATT), a general specification for sending and receiving short pieces of data, known as attributes, over a low-energy link.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] The Bluetooth mesh profile is an exception to this rule, being based on the General Access Profile (GAP).
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Bluetooth mesh profiles use Bluetooth Low Energy to communicate with other Bluetooth Low Energy devices in the network.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Each device can pass the information forward to other Bluetooth Low Energy devices, creating a "mesh" effect – for example, switching off an entire building of lights from a single smartphone.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] There are many profiles for Bluetooth Low Energy devices in healthcare applications.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] "Electronic leash" applications are well-suited to the long battery life possible for "always-on" devices.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Manufacturers of iBeacon devices implement the appropriate specifications for their device to make use of proximity-sensing capabilities supported by Apple's iOS devices.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] An example of proximity sensing usage is WebAuthn Hybrid Transport with cloud-assisted Bluetooth Low Energy (caBLE), allowing roaming authenticators such as smartphones to authenticate with WebAuthn credential (known as passkey).
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Bluetooth Low Energy is used as a proximity check between roaming authenticators and clients (such as personal computers).
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Announced in January 2020, LE Audio is built on top of Bluetooth 5.2 / 5.3.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] It allows the Bluetooth LE protocol to carry audio, with lower battery consumption compared to regular Bluetooth Audio; features like one set of headphones connecting to multiple audio sources or multiple headphones connecting to one source (known as Auracast); and support for hearing aids.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] The standard has a lower minimum latency claim of 20–30 ms vs.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Specifications on the implementation of Basic Audio Profile and Coordinated Set Identification was released in 2021, and the Common Audio Profile and Service in March 2022.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] On 12 July 2022, the Bluetooth SIG announced the completion of Bluetooth LE Audio.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Auracast implements public audio broadcasting services, allowing multiple receivers to connect to a single audio transmitter without going through Bluetooth device pairing first.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] It is a trademark owned by the Bluetooth SIG.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Bluetooth LE–enabled smartphones function as an assistant to control Auracast receivers like headphones and earbuds.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Broadcast Audio URI, marketed as "Scan to Listen", provides information required to connect to the specific audio stream, encoded with a QR code or transmitted using NFC.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Developed by the MIDI Manufacturers Association (MMA) Working Group (now The MIDI Association), there is a formalized Bluetooth LE MIDI (BLE-MIDI) specification, a wireless protocol designed to transmit MIDI data over Bluetooth Low Energy.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] It focuses on power-efficient wireless MIDI communication for devices such as MIDI controllers, keyboards, pedals, etc., that don't continuously stream data – and without significant latency.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Operating systems that support it include Windows 10 Version 1607, macOS and Android.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] In December 2020, the Bluetooth SIG released a draft specification for a wearable exposure-notification service.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] This service allows exposure-notification services on wearable devices to communicate with, and be controlled by, client devices such as smartphones.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Starting in late 2009, Bluetooth Low Energy integrated circuits were announced by a number of manufacturers.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] These ICs commonly use software radio, so updates to the specification can be accommodated through a firmware upgrade.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Current mobile devices are commonly released with hardware and software support for both classic Bluetooth and Bluetooth Low Energy.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Bluetooth Low Energy technology operates in the same spectrum range (the 2.400–2.4835 GHz ISM band) as classic Bluetooth technology, but uses a different set of channels.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Instead of the classic Bluetooth 79 1-MHz channels, Bluetooth Low Energy has 40 2-MHz channels.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Within a channel, data is transmitted using Gaussian frequency shift modulation, similar to classic Bluetooth's Basic Rate scheme.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] The bit rate is 1 Mbit/s (with an option of 2 Mbit/s in Bluetooth 5), and the maximum transmit power is 10 mW (100 mW in Bluetooth 5).
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Further details are given in Volume 6 Part A (Physical Layer Specification) of the Bluetooth Core Specification V4.0.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Bluetooth Low Energy uses frequency hopping to counteract narrowband interference problems.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Classic Bluetooth also uses frequency hopping but the details are different; as a result, while both FCC and ETSI classify Bluetooth technology as an FHSS scheme, Bluetooth Low Energy is classified as a system using digital modulation techniques or a direct-sequence spread spectrum.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] More technical details may be obtained from official specification as published by the Bluetooth SIG.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Note that power consumption is not part of the Bluetooth specification.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] BLE devices are detected through a procedure based on broadcasting advertising packets.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] This is done using 3 separate channels (frequencies), in order to reduce interference.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] The advertising device sends a packet on at least one of these three channels, with a repetition period called the advertising interval.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] For reducing the chance of multiple consecutive collisions, a random delay of up to 10 milliseconds is added to each advertising interval.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] The scanner listens to the channel for a duration called the scan window, which is periodically repeated every scan interval.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] The discovery latency is therefore determined by a probabilistic process and depends on the three parameters (viz., the advertising interval, the scan interval and the scan window).
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] The discovery scheme of BLE adopts a periodic-interval based technique, for which upper bounds on the discovery latency can be inferred for most parametrizations.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Bluetooth Low Energy has security instances such as the Encrypted Advertising Data (EAD) feature allowing some or all of the application data payload that is transmitted in advertising packets, to be encrypted.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] A standard mechanism for the sharing of key material between a broadcasting device and the observers that are intended to receive this data is also defined, so that the data may be decrypted when received.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] All transmitted Bluetooth LE PDUs include a cyclic redundancy check (CRC) that is recalculated and checked by the receiving device for the possibility of the PDU having been changed in flight.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] All Bluetooth Low Energy devices use the Generic Attribute Profile (GATT).
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] The application programming interface offered by a Bluetooth Low Energy aware operating system will typically be based around GATT concepts.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] A device that initiates GATT commands and requests, and accepts responses, for example, a computer or smartphone.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] A device that receives GATT commands and requests, and returns responses, for example, a temperature sensor.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] A data value transferred between client and server, for example, the current battery voltage.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] A collection of related characteristics, which operate together to perform a particular function.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] service includes characteristics for a temperature measurement value, and a time interval between measurements.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] A descriptor provides additional information about a characteristic.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] For instance, a temperature value characteristic may have an indication of its units (e.g.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Celsius), and the maximum and minimum values which the sensor can measure.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Descriptors are optional – each characteristic can have any number of descriptors.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Some service and characteristic values are used for administrative purposes – for instance, the model name and serial number can be read as standard characteristics within the *Generic Access* service.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Services may also include other services as sub-functions; the main functions of the device are so-called *primary* services, and the auxiliary functions they refer to are *secondary* services.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Services, characteristics, and descriptors are collectively referred to as *attributes*, and identified by universally unique identifiers (UUIDs).
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Any implementer may pick a random or pseudorandom UUID for proprietary uses, but the Bluetooth SIG have reserved a range of UUIDs (of the form *xxxxxxxx-0000-1000-8000-00805F9B34FB*) for standard attributes.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] For efficiency, these identifiers are represented as 16-bit or 32-bit values in the protocol, rather than the 128 bits required for a full UUID.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] For example, the *Device Information* service has the short code 0x180A, rather than 0000180A-0000-1000-... .
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] The full list is kept in the Bluetooth Assigned Numbers document online.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] The GATT protocol provides a number of commands for the client to discover information about the server.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Finally, GATT offers *notifications* and *indications*.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] The client may request a notification for a particular characteristic from the server.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] The server can then send the value to the client whenever it becomes available.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] For instance, a temperature sensor server may notify its client every time it takes a measurement.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] This avoids the need for the client to poll the server, which would require the server's radio circuitry to be constantly operational.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] An *indication* is similar to a notification, except that it requires a response from the client, as confirmation that it has received the message.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Bluetooth Low Energy is designed to enable devices to have very low power consumption.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Several chipmakers including Cambridge Silicon Radio, Dialog Semiconductor, Nordic Semiconductor, STMicroelectronics, Cypress Semiconductor, Silicon Labs and Texas Instruments had introduced Bluetooth Low Energy optimized chipsets by 2014.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Devices with peripheral and central roles have different power requirements.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] A study by beacon software company Aislelabs reported that peripherals such as proximity beacons usually function for 1–2 years powered by a 1,000 mAh coin cell battery.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] This is possible because of the power efficiency of Bluetooth Low Energy protocol, which only transmits small packets as compared to Bluetooth Classic which is also suitable for audio and high bandwidth data.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] In contrast, a continuous scan for the same beacons in central role can consume 1,000 mAh in a few hours.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Android and iOS devices also have very different battery impact depending on type of scans and the number of Bluetooth Low Energy devices in the vicinity.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] With newer chipsets and advances in software, by 2014 both Android and iOS phones had negligible power consumption in real-life Bluetooth Low Energy use.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Bluetooth 5 has introduced a new transmission mode with a doubled symbol rate.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Bluetooth LE has been traditionally transmitting 1 bit per symbol so that theoretically the data rate doubles as well.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] However, the new mode doubles the bandwidth from about 1 MHz to about 2 MHz which makes for more interferences on the edge regions.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] The partitioning of the ISM frequency band has not changed being still 40 channels spaced at a distance of 2 MHz.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] This is an essential difference over Bluetooth 2 EDR which also doubled the data rate but was doing that by employing a π/4-DQPSK or 8-DPSK phase modulation on a 1 MHz channel while Bluetooth 5 continues to use just frequency shift keying.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] The traditional transmission of 1 Mbit in the Bluetooth Basic Rate was renamed 1M PHY in Bluetooth 5.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] The new mode at a doubled symbol speed was introduced as the 2M PHY.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] In Bluetooth Low Energy every transmission starts on the 1M PHY leaving it to the application to initiate a switch to the 2M PHY.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] In that case both sender and receiver will switch to the 2M PHY for transmissions.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] This is designed to facilitate firmware updates where the application can switch back to a traditional 1M PHY in case of errors.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] In reality the target device should be close to the programming station (at a few meters).
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Bluetooth 5 has introduced two new modes with lower data rate.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] The symbol rate of the new "Coded PHY" is the same as the Base Rate 1M PHY but in mode S=2 there are two symbols transmitted per data bit.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] In mode S=2 only a simple Pattern Mapping P=1 is used which simply produces the same stuffing bit for each input data bit.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] In mode S=8 there are eight symbols per data bit with a Pattern Mapping P=4 producing contrasting symbol sequences – a 0 bit is encoded as binary 0011 and a 1 bit is encoded as binary 1100.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] In mode S=2 using P=1 the range doubles approximately, while in mode S=8 using P=4 it does quadruple.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] The "LE Coded" transmissions have not only changed the error correction scheme but it uses a fundamentally new packet format.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Each "LE Coded" burst consists of three blocks.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] The switch block ("extended preamble") is transmitted on the LE 1M PHY but it only consists of 10 times a binary '00111100' pattern.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] These 80 bits are not FEC encoded as usual but they are sent directly to the radio channel.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] It is followed by a header block ("FEC Block 1") which is always transmitted in S=8 mode.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] The header block only contains the destination address ("Access Address" / 32 bit) and an encoding flag ("Coding Indicator" / 2 Bit).
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] The Coding Indicator defines the Pattern Mapping used for the following payload block ("FEC Block 2") where S=2 is possible.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] The new packet format of Bluetooth 5 allows transmitting from 2 up to 256 bytes as the payload in a single burst.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] This is a lot more than the maximum of 31 bytes in Bluetooth 4.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] Along with reach measurements this should allow for localisation functions.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] As a whole the quadrupled range—at the same transmission power—is achieved at the expense of a lower data being at an eighth with 125 kbit.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] The old transmission packet format, as it continues to be used in the 1M PHY and 2M PHY modes, has been named "Uncoded" in Bluetooth 5.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/bluetooth-low-energy] The intermediate "LE Coded" S=2 mode allows for a 500 kbit data rate in the payload which is both beneficial for shorter latencies as well lower power consumption as the burst time itself is shorter.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/connectivity-standards-alliance] The **Connectivity Standards Alliance** (**CSA**), formerly known as the **Zigbee Alliance**, is a group of companies that maintain and publish the Zigbee and Matter standards, along with several others.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/connectivity-standards-alliance] Over the years, the Alliance's membership has grown to over 600 companies, including the likes of Amazon, Apple, Comcast, Google, Yandex, Ikea, Heiman, and Samsung SmartThings.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/connectivity-standards-alliance] The CSA has four levels of membership: associate, adopter, participant, and promoter.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/connectivity-standards-alliance] The Alliance also has two regional member groups in China and Europe: The Connectivity Standards Alliance Member Group China (CMGC) is formed by members with a focus on promoting Alliance technologies in the China market.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/connectivity-standards-alliance] The Europe Interest Group (EIG) consisting of 98+ member companies and 216 individual members has a focus on the European market.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/connectivity-standards-alliance] The name Zigbee is a registered trademark of this group, and is not a single technical standard.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/connectivity-standards-alliance] The organization publishes application profiles that allow multiple original equipment manufacturer (OEM) vendors to create interoperable products.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/connectivity-standards-alliance] The relationship between IEEE 802.15.4 and Zigbee is similar to that between IEEE 802.11 and the Wi-Fi Alliance.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/connectivity-standards-alliance] The requirements for membership in the Alliance cause problems for free-software developers working with Zigbee because the annual fee conflicts with the GNU General Public Licence.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/connectivity-standards-alliance] The requirements for developers to join the CSA also conflict with most other free-software licenses.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/connectivity-standards-alliance] The CSA board of directors has been asked to make their license compatible with GPL, but refused.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/connectivity-standards-alliance] Bluetooth has GPL-licensed implementations.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/connectivity-standards-alliance] However, the main Matter SDK is licensed under Apache 2.0 alongside the TypeScript and Rust implementations.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/connectivity-standards-alliance] On May 11, 2021, the Zigbee Alliance announced its rebranding to *Connectivity Standards Alliance*.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] The phrase **smart home** refers to home automation devices that have internet access.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] Home automation, a broader category, includes *any* device that can be monitored or controlled via wireless radio signals, not just those having internet access.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] When connected with the Internet, home sensors and activation devices are an important constituent of the Internet of Things ("IoT").
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] A home automation system typically connects controlled devices to a central smart home hub (sometimes called a "gateway").
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] The user interface for control of the system uses either wall-mounted terminals, tablet or desktop computers, a mobile phone application, or a Web interface that may also be accessible off-site through the Internet.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] Early home automation began with labor-saving machines.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] Self-contained electric or gas powered home appliances became viable in the 1900s with the introduction of electric power distribution and led to the introduction of washing machines (1904), water heaters (1889), refrigerators (1913), sewing machines, dishwashers, and clothes dryers.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] In 1975, the first general purpose home automation network technology, X10, was developed.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] It is a communication protocol for electronic devices.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] It primarily uses electric power transmission wiring for signalling and control, where the signals involve brief radio frequency bursts of digital data, and remains the most widely available.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] By 2012, in the United States, according to ABI Research, 1.5 million home automation systems were installed.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] Per research firm Statista more than 45 million smart home devices will be installed in U.S. homes by the end of the year 2018.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] From 2018 to 2023, the number of U.S. homes equipped with smart devices grew at 10.2% per year to reach 63.43 million by 2023.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] The word "*domotics*" is a contraction of the Latin word for a home (*domus*) and the word *robotics*.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] The word "smart" in "smart home" refers to the system being aware of the state of its devices, which is done through the information and communication technologies (ICT) protocol and the Internet of Things (IoT).
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] In 2011, Microsoft Research found that home automation could involve a high cost of ownership, inflexibility of interconnected devices, and poor manageability.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] When designing and creating a home automation system, engineers take into account several factors including scalability, how well the devices can be monitored and controlled, ease of installation and use for the consumer, affordability, speed, security, and ability to diagnose issues.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] Findings from iControl showed that consumers prioritize ease-of-use over technical innovation, and although consumers recognize that new connected devices have an unparalleled cool factor, they are not quite ready to use them in their own homes yet.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] Historically, systems have been sold as complete systems where the consumer relies on one vendor for the entire system including the hardware, the communications protocol, the central hub, and the user interface.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] However, there are now open hardware and open source software systems which can be used instead of or with proprietary hardware.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] Many of these systems interface with consumer electronics such as the Arduino or Raspberry Pi, which are easily accessible online and in most electronics stores.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] In addition, home automation devices are increasingly interfaced with mobile phones through Bluetooth, allowing for increased affordability and customizability for the user.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] Customers may hesitate to bet their IoT future on proprietary software or hardware devices that use proprietary protocols that may fade or become difficult to customize and interconnect.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] The nature of home automation devices can also be a problem for security, data security and data privacy, since patches to bugs found in the core operating system often do not reach users of older and lower-price devices.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] One set of researchers say that the failure of vendors to support older devices with patches and updates leaves more than 87% of active devices vulnerable.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] Concerns have been raised by tenants renting from landlords who decide to upgrade units with smart home technology.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] These concerns include weak wireless connections that render the door or appliance unusable or impractical; the security of door passcodes kept by the landlord; and the potential invasion of privacy that comes with connecting smart home technologies to home networks.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] Researchers have also conducted user studies to determine what the barriers are for consumers when integrating home automation devices or systems into their daily lifestyle.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] One of the main takeaways was regarding ease of use, as consumers tend to steer towards "plug and play" solutions over more complicated setups.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] One study found that there were large gaps in the mental-models generated by users regarding how the devices actually work.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] Specifically, the findings showed that there was a lot of misunderstanding related to where the data collected by smart devices was stored and how it was used.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] For example, in a smart light setup, one participant thought that her iPad communicated directly with the light, telling it to either turn-off or on.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] In reality, the iPad sends a signal to the cloud system that the company uses (in this case, the Hue Bridge) which then signals directly to the device.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] Overall, this field is still evolving and the nature of each device is constantly changing.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] While technologists work to create more secure, streamlined, and standardized security protocols, consumers also need to learn more about how these devices work and what the implications of putting them in their homes can be.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] The growth of this field is currently limited not only by technology but also by a user's ability to trust a device and integrate it successfully into his/her daily life.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] Utilizing home automation could lead to more efficient and intelligent energy-saving techniques.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] To do this, researchers propose using data from sensors regarding consumer activity within the home to anticipate consumer needs and balance that with energy consumption.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] Furthermore, home automation has a large potential regarding family safety and security.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] According to a 2015 survey done by iControl, the primary drivers of the demand for smart and connected devices are first "personal and family security", and second "excitement about energy savings".
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] Home automation includes a variety of smart security systems and surveillance setups.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] This allows consumers to monitor their homes while away, and to give trusted family members access to that information in case anything bad happens.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] While there are many competing vendors, there are increasing efforts towards open source systems.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] However, there are issues with the current state of home automation including a lack of standardized security measures and deprecation of older devices without backwards compatibility.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] Home automation has high potential for sharing data between family members or trusted individuals for personal security purposes and could lead to energy saving measures with a positive environmental impact in the future.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/home-automation] The home automation market was worth US$64 billion in 2022 and is projected to grow to over $163 billion in 2028.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The field has evolved due to the convergence of multiple technologies, including ubiquitous computing, sensors, embedded systems, and machine learning.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Traditional fields of embedded systems, wireless sensor networks, control systems, and automation independently and collectively enable the Internet of things.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] While in the consumer market, IoT technology is most commonly as smart home products—including devices and appliances like thermostats and smart speakers—the technology's largest applications are in the business and industrial sectors.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Commercial asset tracking and fleet management represent the largest single application of IoT, accounting for 22% of the total market, driven by the need to monitor mobile assets like vehicles and shipping containers.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The largest asset tracking sub-segments in transport & logistics are trailer and intermodal container tracking, reaching 5.8 million and 5.3 million active devices globally at the end of 2024 respectively.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Other major applications include industrial monitoring, smart metering in utilities, and connected healthcare.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Due to their interconnected nature, IoT devices are vulnerable to security breaches and privacy concerns.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] At the same time, the way these devices communicate wirelessly creates regulatory ambiguities, complicating jurisdictional boundaries of the data transfer.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Around 1972, for its remote site use, the Stanford Artificial Intelligence Laboratory developed a computer-controlled vending machine, adapted from a machine rented from Canteen Vending, which sold for cash or, through a computer terminal (Teletype Model 33 KSR), on credit.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Amongst its products were beer, yogurt, and milk.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] It was named *Prancing Pony*, after the name of the room, which was named after an inn in J.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Tolkien's epic fantasy novel The Lord of the Rings.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] A successor version still operates in the Computer Science Department at Stanford, with updated hardware and software.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] While it was initially accessible only on the CMU campus, it gained prominence as the first ARPANET-connected appliance.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Mark Weiser's 1991 paper on ubiquitous computing, "The Computer of the 21st Century", as well as academic venues such as UbiComp and PerCom, produced the contemporary vision of the IoT.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The field gained momentum when Bill Joy envisioned device-to-device communication as part of his "Six Webs" framework, which was presented at the World Economic Forum in Davos in 1999.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The concept of the "Internet of things" and the term itself first appeared in a speech by Peter T.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Lewis to the Congressional Black Caucus Foundation 15th Annual Legislative Weekend in Washington, D.C., published in September 1985.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The primary defining characteristic of the Internet of things has been considered its ability to embed short-range mobile transceivers in various gadgets and daily necessities, enabling new forms of communication between people and things, as well as between things themselves.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Defining the Internet of things as "simply the point in time when more 'things or objects' were connected to the Internet than people", Cisco Systems estimated that the IoT was "born" between 2008 and 2009, with the things/people ratio growing from 0.08 in 2003 to 1.84 in 2010.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The extensive set of applications for IoT devices is often divided into consumer, commercial, industrial, and infrastructure spaces.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] A growing portion of IoT devices is created for consumer use, including connected vehicles, home automation, wearable technology, connected health, and appliances with remote monitoring capabilities.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices are part of the broader concept of home automation, which generally includes lighting, heating and air conditioning, media and security systems, and camera systems.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Moreover, long-term benefits could include energy savings by automatically ensuring lights and electronics are turned off or by making the residents in the home aware of usage.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] A smart home, also known as an automated home, could be based on a platform or hubs that control smart devices and appliances.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] For instance, using Apple's HomeKit, manufacturers can have their home products and accessories controlled by an application in iOS devices such as the iPhone and the Apple Watch.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] This could be a dedicated app or iOS native applications such as Siri.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] This can be demonstrated in the case of Lenovo's Smart Home Essentials, which is a line of smart home devices that are controlled through Apple's Home app or Siri without the need for a Wi-Fi bridge.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] There are also dedicated smart home hubs that are offered as standalone platforms to connect different smart home products.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] These include the Amazon Echo, Google Home, Apple's HomePod, and Samsung's SmartThings Hub.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] In addition to the commercial systems, there are many non-proprietary, open source ecosystems, including Home Assistant, OpenHAB, and Domoticz.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] One key application of a smart home is to assist the elderly and individuals with disabilities.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] These home systems use assistive technology to accommodate an owner's specific disabilities.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Voice control can assist users with sight and mobility limitations while alert systems can be connected directly to cochlear implants worn by individuals with hearing impairments.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] They can also be equipped with additional safety features, including sensors that monitor for medical emergencies such as falls or seizures.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Smart home technology applied in this way can provide users with more freedom and a higher quality of life.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The term "Enterprise IoT" refers to devices used in business and corporate settings.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The **Internet of Medical Things** (**IoMT**) is an application of the IoT for medical and health-related purposes, data collection and analysis for research, and monitoring.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The IoMT has been referenced as "Smart Healthcare", as the technology for creating a digitized healthcare system, connecting available medical resources and healthcare services.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices can be used to enable remote health monitoring and emergency notification systems.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] These health monitoring devices can range from blood pressure and heart rate monitors to advanced devices capable of monitoring specialized implants, such as pacemakers, Fitbit electronic wristbands, or advanced hearing aids.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Some hospitals have begun implementing "smart beds" that can detect when they are occupied and when a patient is attempting to get up.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] It can also adjust itself to ensure appropriate pressure and support are applied to the patient without the manual interaction of nurses.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Specialized sensors can also be equipped within living spaces to monitor the health and general well-being of senior citizens, while ensuring that proper treatment is administered and assisting people in regaining lost mobility via therapy as well.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] These sensors create a network of intelligent sensors that are able to collect, process, transfer, and analyze valuable information in different environments, such as connecting in-home monitoring devices to hospital-based systems.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Other consumer devices to encourage healthy living, such as connected scales or wearable heart monitors, are also a possibility with the IoT.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] End-to-end health monitoring IoT platforms are also available for antenatal and chronic patients, helping one manage health vitals and recurring medication requirements.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Advances in plastic and fabric electronics fabrication methods have enabled ultra-low-cost, use-and-throw IoMT sensors.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] These sensors, along with the required radio-frequency identification electronics, can be fabricated on paper or e-textiles for wireless powered disposable sensing devices.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Applications have been established for point-of-care medical diagnostics, where portability and low system complexity are considered essential.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] As of 2018, IoMT was being applied in the clinical laboratory industry.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IoMT in the insurance industry provides access to better and new types of dynamic information.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] This includes sensor-based solutions such as biosensors, wearables, connected health devices, and mobile apps to track customer behavior.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] This can lead to more accurate underwriting and new pricing models.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The application of the IoT in healthcare plays a fundamental role in managing chronic diseases and in disease prevention and control.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Remote monitoring is made possible through the connection of wireless solutions.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The connectivity enables health practitioners to capture patients' data and apply algorithms in health data analysis.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT can assist in the integration of communications, control, and information processing across various transportation systems.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Application of the IoT extends to all aspects of transportation systems (i.e., the vehicle, the infrastructure, and the driver or user).
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Dynamic interaction between these components of a transport system enables inter- and intra-vehicular communication, smart traffic control, smart parking, electronic toll collection systems, logistics and fleet management, vehicle control, safety, and road assistance.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] In vehicle security applications, IoT-connected GPS trackers can operate for months or years on internal batteries, using low-power wide-area network protocols such as LTE-M to transmit location data to owners via smartphone applications when unauthorized movement is detected.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] In vehicular communication systems, vehicle-to-everything communication (V2X), consists of three main components: vehicle-to-vehicle communication (V2V), vehicle-to-infrastructure communication (V2I), and vehicle-to-pedestrian communication (V2P).
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Eventually, V2X is the first step to autonomous driving and connected road infrastructure.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices can be used to monitor and control the mechanical, electrical, and electronic systems used in various types of buildings (e.g., public and private, industrial, institutions, or residential) in home automation and building automation systems.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Also known as IIoT, industrial IoT devices acquire and analyze data from connected equipment, operational technology (OT), locations, and people.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Combined with operational technology (OT) monitoring devices, IIoT helps regulate and monitor industrial systems.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Additionally, the same implementation can be carried out for automated record updates of asset placement in industrial storage units as the size of the assets can vary from a small screw to the whole motor spare part, and misplacement of such assets can cause a loss of manpower time and money.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT can connect various manufacturing devices equipped with sensing, identification, processing, communication, actuation, and networking capabilities.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Network control and management of manufacturing equipment, asset and situation management, or manufacturing process control enable IoT to be utilized for industrial applications and smart manufacturing.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IoT intelligent systems enable rapid manufacturing and optimization of new products and rapid response to product demands.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Digital control systems, which aim to automate process controls, operator tools, and service information systems, alongside optimizing plant safety and security, fall within the purview of the IIoT.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Furthermore, IoT can also be applied to asset management via predictive maintenance, statistical evaluation, and measurements to maximize reliability.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Industrial management systems can be integrated with smart grids, enabling energy optimization.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Measurements, automated controls, plant optimization, health and safety management, and other functions are provided by networked sensors.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] In addition to general manufacturing, IoT is also used for processes in the industrialization of construction.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] There are numerous IoT applications in farming such as collecting data on temperature, rainfall, humidity, wind speed, pest infestation, and soil content.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] This data can be used to automate farming techniques, make informed decisions to improve quality and quantity, minimize risk and waste, and reduce the effort required to manage crops.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] For example, farmers can now monitor soil temperature and moisture from afar and even apply IoT-acquired data to precision fertilization programs.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The overall goal is that data from sensors, coupled with the farmer's knowledge and intuition about his or her farm, can help increase farm productivity, and also help reduce costs.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] In August 2018, Toyota Tsusho began a partnership with Microsoft to create fish farming tools using the Microsoft Azure application suite for IoT technologies related to water management.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Developed in part by researchers from Kindai University, the water pump mechanisms use artificial intelligence to count the number of fish on a conveyor belt, analyze the number of fish, and deduce the effectiveness of water flow from the data the fish provide.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The FarmBeats project from Microsoft Research that uses TV white space to connect farms is also a part of the Azure Marketplace now.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices are in use to monitor the environments and systems of boats and yachts.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Many pleasure boats are left unattended for days in summer, and months in winter so such devices provide valuable early alerts of boat flooding, fire, and deep discharge of batteries.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Monitoring and controlling operations of sustainable urban and rural infrastructures like bridges, railway tracks and on- and offshore wind farms is a key application of the IoT.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT infrastructure can be used for monitoring any events or changes in structural conditions that can compromise safety and increase risk.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT can benefit the construction industry by cost-saving, time reduction, better quality workday, paperless workflow and increase in productivity.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] It can help in making faster decisions and saving money in Real-Time Data Analytics.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] It can also be used for scheduling repair and maintenance activities efficiently, by coordinating tasks between different service providers and users of these facilities.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices can also be used to control critical infrastructure, like bridges, to provide access to ships.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The usage of IoT devices for monitoring and operating infrastructure is likely to significantly improve incident management and emergency response coordination, and quality of service, up-times and reduce costs of operation in all infrastructure-related areas.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Even areas such as waste management can benefit.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] There are several planned or ongoing large-scale deployments of the IoT to enable better management of cities and systems.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] For example, Songdo, South Korea, the first fully equipped and wired smart city, is gradually being built, with approximately 70 percent of the business district completed as of June 2018.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] A sizeable portion of the city, the first of its kind, is planned to be wired and automated to operate with little or no human intervention.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] In 2014, another application was undergoing a project in Santander, Spain.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] For this deployment, two approaches have been adopted.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] This city of 180,000 inhabitants has already seen 18,000 downloads of its city smartphone app.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The app is connected to 10,000 sensors that enable services like parking search and environmental monitoring.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Additionally, city context information is used in this deployment, aiming to benefit merchants through a spark deals mechanism based on city behavior that aims at maximizing the impact of each notification.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Other examples of large-scale deployments underway include the Sino-Singapore Guangzhou Knowledge City; work on improving air and water quality, reducing noise pollution, and increasing transportation efficiency in San Jose, California; and smart traffic management in western Singapore.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Using its RPMA (Random Phase Multiple Access) technology, San Diego–based Ingenu has built a nationwide public network for low-bandwidth data transmissions using the same unlicensed 2.4 gigahertz spectrum as Wi-Fi.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Ingenu's "Machine Network" covers more than a third of the US population across 35 major cities including San Diego and Dallas.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] French company, Sigfox, commenced building an Ultra Narrowband wireless data network in the San Francisco Bay Area in 2014, the first business to achieve such a deployment in the U.S.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] It subsequently announced it would set up a total of 4000 base stations to cover a total of 30 cities in the U.S. by the end of 2016, making it the largest IoT network coverage provider in the country thus far.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Cisco also participates in smart cities projects.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Cisco has deployed technologies for Smart Wi-Fi, Smart Safety & Security, Smart Lighting, Smart Parking, Smart Transports, Smart Bus Stops, Smart Kiosks, Remote Expert for Government Services (REGS) and Smart Education in the five km area in the city of Vijayawada, India.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Another example of a large deployment is the one completed by New York Waterways in New York City to connect all the city's vessels and be able to monitor them live 24/7.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The network was designed and engineered by Fluidmesh Networks, a Chicago-based company developing wireless networks for critical applications.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The NYWW network is currently providing coverage on the Hudson River, East River, and Upper New York Bay.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] With the wireless network in place, NY Waterway is able to take control of its fleet and passengers in a way that was not previously possible.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] New applications can include security, energy and fleet management, digital signage, public Wi-Fi, paperless ticketing and others.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Significant numbers of energy-consuming devices (e.g., lamps, household appliances, motors, pumps, etc.) already integrate Internet connectivity, which can allow them to communicate with utilities not only to balance power generation but also helps optimize the energy consumption as a whole.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] These devices allow for remote control by users, or central management via a cloud-based interface, and enable functions like scheduling (e.g., remotely powering on or off heating systems, controlling ovens, changing lighting conditions etc.).
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The smart grid is a utility-side IoT application; systems gather and act on energy and power-related information to improve the efficiency of the production and distribution of electricity.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Using advanced metering infrastructure (AMI) Internet-connected devices, electric utilities not only collect data from end-users, but also manage distribution automation devices like transformers.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Environmental monitoring applications of the IoT typically use sensors to assist in environmental protection by monitoring air or water quality, atmospheric or soil conditions, and can even include areas like monitoring the movements of wildlife and their habitats.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Development of resource-constrained devices connected to the Internet also means that other applications like earthquake or tsunami early-warning systems can also be used by emergency services to provide more effective aid.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices in this application typically span a large geographic area and can also be mobile.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] It has been argued that the standardization that IoT brings to wireless sensing will revolutionize this area.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Another example of integrating the IoT is the concept of a "living lab." Living labs integrate and combine research and innovation processes, establishing within a public-private-people-partnership.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Between 2006 and January 2024, there were over 440 living labs (though not all are currently active) that use the IoT to collaborate and share knowledge between stakeholders to co-create innovative and technological products.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] When companies intend to implement and develop IoT services for smart cities, they need to have economic incentives.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The US government plays a key role in smart city projects; changes in policies will help cities to implement the IoT, which provides effectiveness, efficiency, and accuracy of the resources that are being used.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The Internet of Military Things (IoMT) is the application of IoT technologies in the military domain for the purposes of reconnaissance, surveillance, and other combat-related objectives.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] It is heavily influenced by the future prospects of warfare in an urban environment and involves the use of sensors, munitions, vehicles, robots, human-wearable biometrics, and other smart technology that is relevant on the battlefield.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] One of the examples of IOT devices used in the military is the Xaver 1000 system.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The Xaver 1000 was developed by Israel's Camero Tech, which is the latest in the company's line of "through-wall imaging systems." The Xaver line uses millimeter wave (MMW) radar, or radar in the range of 30-300 gigahertz.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] It is equipped with an AI-based life target tracking system as well as its own 3D 'sense-through-the-wall' technology.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The **Internet of Battlefield Things** (**IoBT**) is a project initiated and executed by the U.S.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Army Research Laboratory (ARL) that focuses on the basic science related to the IoT that enhances the capabilities of Army soldiers.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] In 2017, ARL launched the Internet of Battlefield Things Collaborative Research Alliance (IoBT-CRA), establishing a working collaboration between industry, university, and Army researchers to advance the theoretical foundations of IoT technologies and their applications to Army operations.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The **Ocean of Things** project is a DARPA-led program designed to establish an Internet of things across large ocean areas for the purposes of collecting, monitoring, and analyzing environmental and vessel activity data.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The project entails the deployment of about 50,000 floats that house a passive sensor suite that autonomously detects and tracks military and commercial vessels as part of a cloud-based network.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] There are several applications of smart or active packaging in which a QR code or NFC tag is affixed to a product or its packaging.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The tag itself is passive; however, it contains a unique identifier (typically a URL) which enables a user to access digital content about the product via a smartphone.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Strictly speaking, such passive items are not part of the Internet of things, but they can be seen as enablers of digital interactions.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The term "Internet of Packaging" has been coined to describe applications in which unique identifiers are used, to automate supply chains, and are scanned on large scale by consumers to access digital content.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Authentication of the unique identifiers, and thereby of the product itself, is possible via a copy-sensitive digital watermark or copy detection pattern for scanning when scanning a QR code, while NFC tags can encrypt communication.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] In the Internet of Things (IoT), As of April 2026, the number of devices connected and controlled via the Internet has increased.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Applications of IoT technology vary across devices, but many share common characteristics.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT creates opportunities for more direct integration of the physical world into computer-based systems, resulting in efficiency improvements, economic benefits, and reduced human exertions.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IoT Analytics reported there were 16.6 billion IoT devices connected in 2023.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] In 2020, the same firm projected there would be 30 billion devices connected by 2025.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] As of October, 2024, there are around 17 billion.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Ambient intelligence and autonomous control are not part of the original concept of the Internet of things.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Ambient intelligence and autonomous control do not necessarily require Internet structures, either.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] However, there is a shift in research (by companies such as Intel) to integrate the concepts of the IoT and autonomous control, with initial outcomes towards this direction considering objects as the driving force for autonomous IoT.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] An approach in this context is deep reinforcement learning where most of IoT systems provide a dynamic and interactive environment.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Training an agent (i.e., IoT device) to behave smartly in such an environment cannot be addressed by conventional machine learning algorithms such as supervised learning.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Through a reinforcement learning approach, a learning agent can sense the environment's state (e.g., sensing home temperature), perform actions (e.g., turn HVAC on or off) and learn by maximizing accumulated rewards it receives.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IoT intelligence can be offered at three levels: IoT devices, Edge/Fog nodes, and cloud computing.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The need for intelligent control and decision at each level depends on the time sensitiveness of the IoT application.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] For example, an autonomous vehicle's camera needs to make real-time obstacle detection to avoid an accident.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] This fast decision making would not be possible if it is necessary to transfer data from the vehicle to cloud instances and return the predictions back to the vehicle.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Instead, the operation should be performed locally in the vehicle.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Integrating advanced machine learning algorithms, including deep learning, into IoT devices is an active research area to make smart objects closer to reality.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Moreover, it is possible to get the most value out of IoT deployments through analyzing IoT data, extracting hidden information, and predicting control decisions.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] A wide variety of machine learning techniques have been used in IoT domain ranging from traditional methods such as regression, support vector machine, and random forest to advanced ones such as convolutional neural networks, LSTM, and variational autoencoder.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Modern IoT products and solutions in the marketplace use a variety of different technologies to support such context-aware automation, but more sophisticated forms of intelligence are requested to permit sensor units and intelligent cyber-physical systems to be deployed in real environments.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IoT system architecture, in its simplistic view, consists of three tiers: Tier 1: Devices, Tier 2: the Edge Gateway, and Tier 3: the Cloud.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Devices include networked things, such as the sensors and actuators found in IoT equipment, particularly those that use protocols such as Modbus, Bluetooth, Zigbee, or proprietary protocols, to connect to an Edge Gateway.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The Edge Gateway layer consists of sensor data aggregation systems called Edge Gateways that provide functionality, such as pre-processing of the data, securing connectivity to cloud, using systems such as WebSockets, the event hub, and, even in some cases, edge analytics or fog computing.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Edge Gateway layer is also required to give a common view of the devices to the upper layers to facilitate in easier management.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The final tier includes the cloud application built for IoT using the microservices architecture, which are usually polyglot and inherently secure in nature using HTTPS/OAuth.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] It includes various database systems that store sensor data, such as time series databases or asset stores using backend data storage systems (e.g.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The cloud tier in most cloud-based IoT system features event queuing and messaging system that handles communication that transpires in all tiers.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Some experts classified the three-tiers in the IoT system as edge, platform, and enterprise and these are connected by proximity network, access network, and service network, respectively.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IoT requires huge scalability in the network space to handle the surge of devices.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IETF 6LoWPAN can be used to connect devices to IP networks.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] With billions of devices being added to the Internet space, IPv6 may play an important role in handling the network layer scalability.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IETF's Constrained Application Protocol, ZeroMQ, and MQTT can provide lightweight data transport.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] In practice, many groups of IoT devices are hidden behind gateway nodes and may not have unique addresses.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Also, the vision of everything being interconnected is not needed for most applications as it is mainly the data that needs interconnecting at a higher layer.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Fog computing is a viable alternative to prevent such a large burst of data flow through the Internet.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The edge devices' computation power to analyze and process data is extremely limited.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Limited processing power is a key attribute of IoT devices as their purpose is to supply data about physical objects while remaining autonomous.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Heavy processing requirements use more battery power, harming IoT's ability to operate.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Scalability is easy because IoT devices simply supply data through the Internet to a server with sufficient processing power.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Performance is improved, especially for huge IoT systems with millions of nodes.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Conventional IoT is connected via a mesh network and led by a major head node (centralized controller).
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The head node decides how a data is created, stored, and transmitted.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] In contrast, decentralized IoT attempts to divide IoT systems into smaller divisions.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The head node authorizes partial decision-making power to lower level sub-nodes under mutual agreed policy.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Some approaches to decentralized IoT attempt to address the limited bandwidth and hashing capacity of battery-powered or wireless IoT devices via blockchain.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] In semi-open or closed loops (i.e., value chains, whenever a global finality can be settled) the IoT is often analyzed as a complex system due to the large number of different interactions between autonomous actors, and its capacity to integrate new actors.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] At the overall stage (full open loop) it will likely be seen as a chaotic environment (since systems always have finality).
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] As a practical approach, not all elements on the Internet of things run in a global, public space.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Subsystems are often implemented to mitigate the risks of privacy, control and reliability.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] For example, domestic robotics (domotics) running inside a smart home might only share data within and be available via a local network.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Managing and controlling a high dynamic ad hoc IoT things/devices network is a complex task within traditional network architecture, software-defined networking (SDN) provides a dynamic approach that better fits the special requirements of IoT applications.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The exact scale of the Internet of things is unknown, with quotes of billions or trillions often quoted at the beginning of IoT articles.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] In 2015, there were 83 million smart devices in people's homes.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] This number is expected to grow to 193 million devices by 2020.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] In 2023, the number of connected IoT devices will reach 16.6 billion.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The number of online-capable devices grew 31% from 2016 to 2017 to reach 8.4 billion.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] In the Internet of things, the precise geographic location of a thing—and also the precise geographic dimensions of a thing—can be critical.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] (Note that some things on the Internet of things will be sensors, and sensor location is usually important.) The GeoWeb and Digital Earth are applications that become possible when things can become organized and connected by location.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] However, the challenges that remain include the constraints of variable spatial scales, the need to handle massive amounts of data, and an indexing for fast search and neighbour operations.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] On the Internet of things, if things are able to take actions on their own initiative, this human-centric mediation role is eliminated.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Thus, the time-space context that we as humans take for granted must be given a central role in this information ecosystem.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Just as standards play a key role on the Internet and the Web, geo-spatial standards will play a key role on the Internet of things.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Many IoT devices have the potential to take a piece of this market.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] For improved user interaction, some technology leaders are joining forces to create standards for communication between devices to solve this problem.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Others are turning to the concept of predictive interaction of devices, "where collected data is used to predict and trigger actions on the specific devices" while making them work together.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Social Internet of things (SIoT) is a new kind of IoT that focuses on the importance of social interaction and relationships between IoT devices.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IoT defines a device with an identity like a citizen in a community and connects them to the Internet to provide services to its users.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] SIoT defines a social network for IoT devices only to interact with each other for different goals that to serve human.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] SIoT is different from the original IoT in terms of the collaboration characteristics.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IoT is passive; it was set to serve for dedicated purposes with existing IoT devices in a predetermined system.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] SIoT is active, it was programmed and managed by AI to serve for unplanned purposes with mix and match of potential IoT devices from different systems that benefit its users.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices with built-in sociability are able to broadcast their abilities or functionality, which can be used to discover and share information with other IoT devices in the same or nearby network, realizing SIoT.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Facilitating further functionality with these abilities could be helpful during emergencies.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IoT sensors on the vehicles, road and traffic lights monitor the conditions of the vehicles and drivers and alert when attention is needed, and also coordinate themselves automatically to ensure autonomous driving is working normally.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] If a crash happens, the IoT camera will inform the nearest hospital and police station for help.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] System security is always a concern for any technology, and it is more crucial for SIoT as not only the security of oneself needs to be considered, but also the mutual trust mechanism between collaborative IoT devices from time to time, from place to place.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Another critical challenge for SIoT is the accuracy and reliability of the sensors.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p01] In most circumstances, IoT sensors would need to respond quickly to avoid accidents, injury, and loss of life.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] There are many technologies that enable the IoT.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The original idea of the Auto-ID Center is based on RFID tags and distinct identification through the Electronic Product Code.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] This has evolved into objects having an IP address or URI.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] An alternative view, from the world of the Semantic Web focuses instead on making all things (not just those electronic, smart, or RFID-enabled) addressable by the existing naming protocols, such as URI.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The objects themselves do not converse, but they may now be referred to by other agents, such as powerful centralised servers acting for their human owners.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Integration with the Internet implies that devices will use an IP address as a distinct identifier.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Due to the limited address space of IPv4 (which allows for 4.3 billion different addresses), objects in the IoT will have to use the next generation of the Internet protocol (IPv6) to scale to the extremely large address space required.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Internet-of-things devices additionally will benefit from the stateless address auto-configuration present in IPv6, as it reduces the configuration overhead on the hosts, and the IETF 6LoWPAN header compression.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] To a large extent, the future of the Internet of things will not be possible without the support of IPv6; and consequently, the global adoption of IPv6 in the coming years will be critical for the successful development of the IoT in the future.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Different technologies have different roles in a protocol stack.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] This is a list of technical standards for the IoT, most of which are open standards, and the standards organizations that aspire to successfully setting them.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Some scholars and activists argue that the IoT can be used to create new models of civic engagement if device networks can be open to user control and interoperable platforms.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Howard, a professor and author, writes that political life in both democracies and authoritarian regimes will be shaped by the way the IoT will be used for civic engagement.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] For that to happen, he argues that any connected device should be able to divulge a list of the "ultimate beneficiaries" of its sensor data and that individual citizens should be able to add new organisations to the beneficiary list.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] In addition, he argues that civil society groups need to start developing their IoT strategy for making use of data and engaging with the public.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] One of the key drivers of the IoT is data.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The success of the idea of connecting devices to make them more efficient is dependent upon access to and storage & processing of data.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] For this purpose, companies working on the IoT collect data from multiple sources and store it in their cloud network for further processing.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] This leaves the door wide open for privacy and security dangers and single point vulnerability of multiple systems.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The other issues pertain to consumer choice and ownership of data and how it is used.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Though still in their infancy, regulations and governance regarding these issues of privacy, security, and data ownership continue to develop.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Some examples of legislation that is relevant to privacy and data collection are: the US Privacy Act of 1974, OECD Guidelines on the Protection of Privacy and Transborder Flows of Personal Data of 1980, and the EU Directive 95/46/EC of 1995.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] However, the FTC stopped at just making recommendations for now.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] A resolution passed by the Senate in March 2015, is already being considered by the Congress.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] This resolution recognized the need for formulating a National Policy on IoT and the matter of privacy, security and spectrum.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Approved on 28 September 2018, California Senate Bill No.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Several standards for the IoT industry are actually being established relating to automobiles because most concerns arising from use of connected cars apply to healthcare devices as well.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] In fact, the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) is preparing cybersecurity guidelines and a database of best practices to make automotive computer systems more secure.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] A recent report from the World Bank examines the challenges and opportunities in government adoption of IoT.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] In early December 2021, the U.K. government introduced the Product Security and Telecommunications Infrastructure bill (PST), an effort to legislate IoT distributors, manufacturers, and importers to meet certain cybersecurity standards.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The bill also seeks to improve the security credentials of consumer IoT devices.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] For example, wireless connectivity for IoT devices can be done using Bluetooth, Wi-Fi, Wi-Fi HaLow, Zigbee, Z-Wave, LoRa, NB-IoT, Cat M1 as well as completely custom proprietary radios – each with its own advantages and disadvantages; and unique support ecosystem.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The IoT's amorphous computing nature is also a problem for security, since patches to bugs found in the core operating system often do not reach users of older and lower-price devices.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] One set of researchers says that the failure of vendors to support older devices with patches and updates leaves more than 87% of active Android devices vulnerable.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Howard, a professor and author, writes that the Internet of things offers immense potential for empowering citizens, making government transparent, and broadening information access.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Howard cautions, however, that privacy threats are enormous, as is the potential for social control and political manipulation.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Concerns about privacy have led many to consider the possibility that big data infrastructures such as the Internet of things and data mining are inherently incompatible with privacy.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Key challenges of increased digitalization in the water, transport or energy sector are related to privacy and cybersecurity which necessitate an adequate response from research and policymakers alike.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Writer Adam Greenfield claims that IoT technologies are not only an invasion of public space but are also being used to perpetuate normative behavior, citing an instance of billboards with hidden cameras that tracked the demographics of passersby who stopped to read the advertisement.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The Internet of Things Council compared the increased prevalence of digital surveillance due to the Internet of things to the concept of the panopticon described by Jeremy Bentham in the 18th century.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The assertion is supported by the works of French philosophers Michel Foucault and Gilles Deleuze.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] In *Discipline and Punish: The Birth of the Prison*, Foucault asserts that the panopticon was a central element of the discipline society developed during the Industrial Era.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Foucault also argued that the discipline systems established in factories and school reflected Bentham's vision of panopticism.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] In his 1992 paper "Postscripts on the Societies of Control", Deleuze wrote that the discipline society had transitioned into a control society, with the computer replacing the panopticon as an instrument of discipline and control while still maintaining the qualities similar to that of panopticism.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Peter-Paul Verbeek, a professor of philosophy of technology at the University of Twente, Netherlands, writes that technology already influences our moral decision making, which in turn affects human agency, privacy and autonomy.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] He cautions against viewing technology merely as a human tool and advocates instead to consider it as an active agent.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Tim O'Reilly believes that the way companies sell IoT devices to consumers is misplaced, disputing the notion that the IoT is about gaining efficiency from putting all kinds of devices online and postulating that, "IoT is really about human augmentation.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Editorials at WIRED have also expressed concern, one stating, "What you're about to lose is your privacy.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) expressed concern regarding the ability of IoT to erode people's control over their own lives.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The ACLU wrote that "There's simply no way to forecast how these immense powers – disproportionately accumulating in the hands of corporations seeking financial advantage and governments craving ever more control – will be used.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] In response to rising concerns about privacy and smart technology, in 2007, the British Government stated it would follow formal Privacy by Design principles when implementing its smart metering program.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The program would lead to the replacement of traditional power meters with smart power meters, which could track and manage energy usage more accurately.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] However the British Computer Society is doubtful these principles were ever actually implemented.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] In 2009, the Dutch Parliament rejected a similar smart metering program, basing their decision on privacy concerns.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The Dutch program later revised and passed in 2011.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] A challenge for producers of IoT applications is to clean, process and interpret the vast amount of data that is gathered by the sensors.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] There is a solution proposed for the analytics of the information referred to as Wireless Sensor Networks.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] These networks share data among sensor nodes that are sent to a distributed system for the analytics of the sensory data.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Another challenge is the storage of this bulk data.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Depending on the application, there could be high data acquisition requirements, which in turn lead to high storage requirements.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] In 2013, the Internet was estimated to be responsible for consuming 5% of the total energy produced, and a "daunting challenge to power" IoT devices to collect and even store data still remains.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Data silos, although a common challenge of legacy systems, still commonly occur with the implementation of IoT devices, particularly within manufacturing.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] As there are a lot of benefits to be gained from IoT and IIoT devices, the means in which the data is stored can present serious challenges without the principles of autonomy, transparency, and interoperability being considered.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The challenges do not occur by the device itself, but the means in which databases and data warehouses are set up.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] These challenges were identified by Keller (2021) when investigating the IT and application landscape of I4.0 implementation within German M&E manufacturers.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Security is the biggest concern in adopting Internet of things technology, with concerns that rapid development is happening without appropriate consideration of the profound security challenges involved and the regulatory changes that might be necessary.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The rapid development of the Internet of Things (IoT) has allowed billions of devices to connect to the network.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Due to too many connected devices and the limitation of communication security technology, various security issues gradually appear in the IoT.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Most of the technical security concerns are similar to those of conventional servers, workstations and smartphones.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] These concerns include using weak authentication, forgetting to change default credentials, unencrypted messages sent between devices, SQL injections, man-in-the-middle attacks, and poor handling of security updates.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] However, many IoT devices have severe operational limitations on the computational power available to them.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] These constraints often make them unable to directly use basic security measures such as implementing firewalls or using strong cryptosystems to encrypt their communications with other devices - and the low price and consumer focus of many devices makes a robust security patching system uncommon.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Rather than conventional security vulnerabilities, fault injection attacks are on the rise and targeting IoT devices.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] A fault injection attack is a physical attack on a device to purposefully introduce faults in the system to change the intended behavior.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Faults might happen unintentionally due to environmental noises and electromagnetic fields.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] There are ideas stemming from control-flow integrity (CFI) to prevent fault injection attacks and system recovery to a healthy state before the fault.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Computer-controlled devices in automobiles such as brakes, engine, locks, hood and trunk releases, horn, heat, and dashboard have been shown to be vulnerable to attackers who have access to the on-board network.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] In some cases, vehicle computer systems are Internet-connected, allowing them to be exploited remotely.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] By 2008, security researchers had shown the ability to remotely control pacemakers without authority.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Later, hackers demonstrated remote control of insulin pumps and implantable cardioverter defibrillators.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Poorly secured Internet-accessible IoT devices can also be subverted to attack others.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] In 2016, a distributed denial of service attack powered by Internet of things devices running the Mirai malware took down a DNS provider and major web sites.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The Mirai Botnet had infected roughly 65,000 IoT devices within the first 20 hours.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Eventually, the infections increased to around 200,000 to 300,000 infections.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Brazil, Colombia and Vietnam made up of 41.5% of the infections.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The Mirai Botnet had singled out specific IoT devices that consisted of DVRs, IP cameras, routers and printers.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] These sorts of attacks have caused security experts to view IoT as a real threat to Internet services.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] National Intelligence Council in an unclassified report maintains that it would be hard to deny "access to networks of sensors and remotely-controlled objects by enemies of the United States, criminals, and mischief makers...
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] An open market for aggregated sensor data could serve the interests of commerce and security no less than it helps criminals and spies identify vulnerable targets.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Thus, massively parallel sensor fusion may undermine social cohesion, if it proves to be fundamentally incompatible with Fourth-Amendment guarantees against unreasonable search." In general, the intelligence community views the Internet of things as a rich source of data.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] There have been a range of responses to concerns over security.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The Internet of Things Security Foundation (IoTSF) was launched on 23 September 2015 with a mission to secure the Internet of things by promoting knowledge and best practices.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Its founding board is made up of technology providers and telecommunications companies.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] In addition, large IT companies are continually developing innovative solutions to ensure the security of IoT devices.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] In 2017, Mozilla launched Project Things, which allows to route IoT devices through a safe Web of Things gateway.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] As per the estimates from KBV Research, the overall IoT security market would grow at 27.9% rate during 2016–2022 as a result of growing infrastructural concerns and diversified usage of Internet of things.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Governmental regulation is argued by some to be necessary to secure IoT devices and the wider Internet – as market incentives to secure IoT devices is insufficient.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] It was found that due to the nature of most of the IoT development boards, they generate predictable and weak keys which make it easy to be utilized by man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] However, various hardening approaches were proposed by many researchers to resolve the issue of SSH weak implementation and weak keys.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] IoT security within the field of manufacturing presents different challenges and varying perspectives.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Within the EU and Germany, data protection is constantly referenced throughout manufacturing and digital policy, particularly that of I4.0.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] However, the attitude towards data security differs from the enterprise perspective, whereas there is an emphasis on less data protection in the form of GDPR, as the data being collected from IoT devices in the manufacturing sector does not display personal details.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Yet, research has indicated that manufacturing experts are concerned about "data security for protecting machine technology from international competitors with the ever-greater push for interconnectivity".
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] IoT systems are typically controlled by event-driven smart apps that take as input either sensed data, user inputs, or other external triggers (from the Internet) and command one or more actuators towards providing different forms of automation.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Examples of sensors include smoke detectors, motion sensors, and contact sensors.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Examples of actuators include smart locks, smart power outlets, and door controls.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Popular control platforms on which third-party developers can build smart apps that interact wirelessly with these sensors and actuators include Samsung's SmartThings, Apple's HomeKit, and Amazon's Alexa, among others.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Detecting flaws that lead to such states, requires a holistic view of installed apps, component devices, their configurations, and more importantly, how they interact.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Recently, researchers from the University of California Riverside have proposed IotSan, a novel practical system that uses model checking as a building block to reveal "interaction-level" flaws by identifying events that can lead the system to unsafe states.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] They have evaluated IotSan on the Samsung SmartThings platform.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] From 76 manually configured systems, IotSan detects 147 vulnerabilities (i.e., violations of safe physical states/properties).
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Given widespread recognition of the evolving nature of the design and management of the Internet of things, sustainable and secure deployment of IoT solutions must design for "anarchic scalability".
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Application of the concept of anarchic scalability can be extended to physical systems (i.e. controlled real-world objects), by virtue of those systems being designed to account for uncertain management futures.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] This hard anarchic scalability thus provides a pathway forward to fully realize the potential of Internet-of-things solutions by selectively constraining physical systems to allow for all management regimes without risking physical failure.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Brown University computer scientist Michael Littman has argued that successful execution of the Internet of things requires consideration of the interface's usability as well as the technology itself.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] A concern regarding Internet-of-things technologies pertains to the environmental impacts of the manufacture, use, and eventual disposal of all these semiconductor-rich devices.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Modern electronics are replete with a wide variety of heavy metals and rare-earth metals, as well as highly toxic synthetic chemicals.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] This makes them extremely difficult to properly recycle.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Electronic components are often incinerated or placed in regular landfills.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Furthermore, the human and environmental cost of mining the rare-earth metals that are integral to modern electronic components continues to grow.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] This leads to societal questions concerning the environmental impacts of IoT devices over their lifetime.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The Electronic Frontier Foundation has raised concerns that companies can use the technologies necessary to support connected devices to intentionally disable or "brick" their customers' devices via a remote software update or by disabling a service necessary to the operation of the device.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] In one example, home automation devices sold with the promise of a "Lifetime Subscription" were rendered useless after Nest Labs acquired Revolv and made the decision to shut down the central servers the Revolv devices had used to operate.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Owners should be free to point their devices to a different server or collaborate on improved software.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] But such action violates the United States DMCA section 1201, which only has an exemption for "local use".
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] This forces tinkerers who want to keep using their own equipment into a legal grey area.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] EFF thinks buyers should refuse electronics and software that prioritize the manufacturer's wishes above their own.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Examples of post-sale manipulations include Google Nest Revolv, disabled privacy settings on Android, Sony disabling Linux on PlayStation 3, and enforced EULA on Wii U.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Kevin Lonergan at *Information Age*, a business technology magazine, has referred to the terms surrounding the IoT as a "terminology zoo".
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The lack of clear terminology is not "useful from a practical point of view" and a "source of confusion for the end user".
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] A company operating in the IoT space could be working in anything related to sensor technology, networking, embedded systems, or analytics.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Regarding IIoT, an industrial sub-field of IoT, the Industrial Internet Consortium's Vocabulary Task Group has created a "common and reusable vocabulary of terms" to ensure "consistent terminology" across publications issued by the Industrial Internet Consortium.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] IoT One has created an IoT Terms Database including a New Term Alert to be notified when a new term is published.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] As of March 2020, this database aggregates 807 IoT-related terms, while keeping material "transparent and comprehensive".
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Despite a shared belief in the potential of the IoT, industry leaders and consumers are facing barriers to adopting IoT technology more widely.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Mike Farley argued in Forbes that while IoT solutions appeal to early adopters, they either lack interoperability or a clear use case for end-users.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] A study by Ericsson regarding the adoption of IoT among Danish companies suggests that many struggle "to pinpoint exactly where the value of IoT lies for them".
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] As for IoT, especially in regard to consumer IoT, information about a user's daily routine is collected so that the "things" around the user can cooperate to provide better services that fulfill personal preferences.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] When the collected information which describes a user in detail travels through multiple hops in a network, due to a diverse integration of services, devices and network, the information stored on a device is vulnerable to privacy violation by compromising nodes existing in an IoT network.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] For example, on 21 October 2016, a multiple distributed denial of service (DDoS) attacks systems operated by domain name system provider Dyn, which caused the inaccessibility of several websites, such as GitHub, Twitter, and others.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] This attack is executed through a botnet consisting of a large number of IoT devices including IP cameras, gateways, and even baby monitors.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Information privacy regulations also require organisations to practice "reasonable security".
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] As each organisation's environment is unique, it can prove challenging to demonstrate what "reasonable security" is and what potential risks could be involved for the business.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] According to antivirus provider Kaspersky, there were 639 million data breaches of IoT devices in 2020 and 1.5 billion breaches in the first six months of 2021.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] One method of overcoming the barrier of safety issues is the introduction of standards and certification of devices.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] In 2024, two voluntary and non-competing programs were proposed and launched in the United States: the US Cyber Trust Mark from The Federal Communications Commission and CSA's IoT Device Security Specification from the Connectivity Standards Alliance.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The programs incorporate international expertise, with the CSA mark recognized by the Singapore Cybersecurity Agency.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Compliance means that IoT devices can resist hacking, control hijacking and theft of confidential data.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Some of these companies risk being "kodaked" – "Kodak was a market leader until digital disruption eclipsed film photography with digital photos" – failing to "see the disruptive forces affecting their industry" and "to truly embrace the new business models the disruptive change opens up".
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] According to a 2018 study, 70–75% of IoT deployments were stuck in the pilot or prototype stage, unable to reach scale due in part to a lack of business planning.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Even though scientists, engineers, and managers across the world are continuously working to create and exploit the benefits of IoT products, there are some flaws in the governance, management and implementation of such projects.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Despite tremendous forward momentum in the field of information and other underlying technologies, IoT still remains a complex area and the problem of how IoT projects are managed still needs to be addressed.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] IoT projects must be run differently than simple and traditional IT, manufacturing or construction projects.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Because IoT projects have longer project timelines, a lack of skilled resources and several security/legal issues, there is a need for new and specifically designed project processes.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/matter-standard] Matter originated in December 2019 as the Project Connected Home over IP (CHIP) working group, founded by Amazon, Apple, Google, and the Connectivity Standards Alliance (when it was the Zigbee Alliance).
[src:matter-protocol-deep/matter-standard] Subsequent members include IKEA, Huawei, Heiman, and Schneider.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/matter-standard] Version 1.0 of the specification was published on 4 October 2022.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/matter-standard] The Matter software development kit is open-source under the Apache License.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/matter-standard] A software development kit (SDK) is provided royalty-free, though the ability to commission a finished product into a Matter network in the field mandates certification and membership fees, entailing both one-time, recurring, and per-product costs.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/matter-standard] This is enforced using a public key infrastructure (PKI) and so-called device attestation certificates.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/matter-standard] Matter-compatible software updates for many existing hubs became available in late 2022, with Matter-enabled devices and software updates starting to release in 2023.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/matter-standard] The primary goal of Matter is to improve interoperability for the current smart home ecosystem.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/matter-standard] CSA and its members aim for the Matter logo to become ubiquitous and for consumers to instantly recognise it as a smart home device that will "just work".
[src:matter-protocol-deep/matter-standard] However, Matter logos do not imply that devices will "just work"; infrastructure is also still required for full functionality, like a Wi-Fi network (which may need to be dual-band) and a Matter controller, and often, an app for each kind of device.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/matter-standard] In December 2019, Amazon, Apple, Google, Samsung SmartThings and the Zigbee Alliance announced the collaboration and formation of the working group of Project Connected Home over IP.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/matter-standard] The goal of the project is to simplify development for smart home product brands and manufacturers while increasing the compatibility of the products for consumers.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/matter-standard] The standard operates on Internet Protocol (IP) and functions via one or more controllers that connect and manage devices within a local network, eliminating the need for multiple proprietary hubs for each ecosystem.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/matter-standard] Matter-certified products are engineered to operate locally and do not depend on an internet connection for their core functions.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/matter-standard] Leveraging IPv6 addressing, the standard facilitates seamless communication with cloud services.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/matter-standard] Its goal is to facilitate interoperability among smart home devices, mobile apps, and cloud services, employing a specific suite of IP-based networking technologies such as mDNS and IPv6.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/matter-standard] By adhering to a network design that operates at the Application Layer of the OSI 7 layer model, Matter differs from protocols like Zigbee or Z-Wave and theoretically can function on any IPv6-enabled network.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/matter-standard] Presently, official support is limited to Wi-Fi, Ethernet, and the wireless mesh network Thread.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/matter-standard] Updates to the standard are planned to occur biannually.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/matter-standard] For future versions, the working group has been working on support for ambient motion and presence sensing, environmental sensing and controls, closure sensors, energy management, Wi-Fi access points, cameras, and major appliances.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/matter-standard] CSA maintains the official list of Matter-certified products, and restricts use of the Matter logo to certified devices.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/matter-standard] Matter product certification is also stored on the CSA's Distributed Compliance Ledger (DCL), which publishes attestation information about certified devices.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/thread-network-protocol] In July 2014, the Thread Group alliance was formed as an industry group to develop, maintain and drive adoption of Thread as an industry networking standard for IoT applications.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/thread-network-protocol] Thread Group provides certification for components and products to ensure adherence to the spec.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/thread-network-protocol] Initial members were ARM Holdings, Big Ass Solutions, NXP Semiconductors/Freescale, Google-subsidiary Nest Labs, OSRAM, Samsung, Silicon Labs, Somfy, Tyco International, Qualcomm, and the Yale lock company.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/thread-network-protocol] In August 2018, Apple joined the group, and released its first Thread product, the HomePod Mini, in late 2020.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/thread-network-protocol] The Thread protocol specification is available at no cost.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/thread-network-protocol] Thread uses IPv6 over Low-Power Wireless Personal Area Networks (6LoWPAN), which, in turn, uses LR-WPAN as defined by the IEEE 802.15.4 wireless protocol with mesh communication (in the 2.4 GHz spectrum), as do Zigbee and other systems.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/thread-network-protocol] However, Thread is IP-addressable, with cloud access and AES encryption.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/thread-network-protocol] A BSD-licensed open-source implementation of Thread called *OpenThread* is available from and managed by Google.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/thread-network-protocol] The OpenThread network simulator, a part of the OpenThread implementation, simulates Thread networks using OpenThread POSIX instances.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/thread-network-protocol] The simulator utilises discrete-event simulation and allows for visualisation of communications through a web interface.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/thread-network-protocol] A Thread border router is a device that provides bidirectional Internet Protocol connectivity between a Thread network and another physical network, such as Wi-Fi or Ethernet.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/thread-network-protocol] It enables communication between Thread devices and other local networks or the Internet.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/thread-network-protocol] A Thread network is a low-power mesh network using the IEEE 802.15.4 protocol in the 2.4 GHz ISM radio band, and a border router translates between such a network another physical network, allows for service discovery across network boundaries, and enables external commissioning of Thread devices.
[src:matter-protocol-deep/thread-network-protocol] Without a border router, Thread devices would be isolated from other networks and the Internet.
